What people are saying
By Mairwen1
“Julius Caesar’s Vanity Project”
Jun 2022
This is one of 5 ancient Roman forums near the Colosseum. It’s easy to get very confused around the forums. It’s hard to tell where one starts and another ends and we struggled with picking out which ruin was which. This section was built by Julius Caesar in 46 BC. He promoted the idea of a new forum area on the basis that the already existing Roman Forum was overcrowded and too small. In reality, it was all about self-promotion. The main feature was the Temple of Venus Genetrix which celebrated his victory over his great rival, Pompey. He took the opportunity to elevate the status of his family by claiming that they were descended from the goddess, Venus Genetrix. He placed a large statue of himself on his favourite horse, centre-stage in the middle of the new forum. Weirdly the horse had human feet - no idea why. The forum was designed in a 100m long, rectangular shape and paved with travertine, with towering columned porticoes along three sides. The temple stood at one end and a hall was added at the other end behind the Curia. Caesar definitely didn’t cut corners. The cost was exorbitant but was mainly funded from the public purse with the wealth from the conquest of Gaul. It was said to be between 60 and 100 million sestertius, a staggering sum when the cost of maintaining a Roman legion was only 12 million a year. Not much remains of Casesar’s forum. Three columns of the temple have survived, some of the travertine paving is still in place and some of the columns from the portico are still standing. Nothing remains of the equestrian statue. NOTE: Entry is included in the Colosseum/Forum/Palatino ticket. You can see some of Caesar’s Forum for free from the roadside if you are walking along the Via Fiori Imperiali towards the Colosseum (it’s on the right hand side).
By Bandit-One
“Still impressive”
Oct 2021
The Foro di Cesare (or Forum Iulium or Forum Julium, Forum Caesaris) dates back to 46BC. That's more than 2000 years of history looking at you. Even though a lot is in ruins, there is indeed a lot to see still. Thought originally to be an expansion of the Forum Romanum this place later on had two additional purposes: a place for public business that was related to the Senate in addition to a shrine for Caesar himself. It's a really impressive sight and must have been breathtaking back in its day. Well, it still IS to this day. And then there you also got the Chiesa Santi Luca e Martina martiri, the Curia Iulia, the Chiesa di San Giuseppe dei Falegnami, the Largo Romolo e Remo, the Tempio di Venere Genitrice, the Tempio della Pace and the Statua di Cesare of the man himself on site. A very rewarding visit. Especially if you have the time to get to know the history and background a bit. Be it by book, by the plaques around the site or by a guided tour. Surely a must-do when in Rome.

dapper777
Monaco66,929 contributions
Memorable experience
Oct 2020
It is located in the Imperial Forum between the Capitol and the Via dei Fori Imperiali, but in its time it was contiguous to the Forum of Trajan.
The visible part of the Forum, after excavations and adjustments
made around 1930, corresponds to little more than the half of the original surface, but other excavations are still underway.
The Forum is accessed from Clivo Argentario, after skirting a large semicircular space (from the Trajan age) with traces of
double pavement for the insulation of the rooms below, which was originally covered by a barrel vault, intended as a public latrine.
Today, of the Temple of Venus Genetrix, renovated by Trajan in 113 AD, remain only the base of the podium and three columns (almost completely redone) with Corinthian capitals and a piece of the entablature.
Look for a guided tour with multimedia system, the evening one around 7:00 pm is more suggestive and does not last more than an hour.
Admission fee is around € 15, with internet booking sites.
Recommended.
Written April 18, 2021

ChiefGuru
Decatur, IN3,300 contributions
Built by Gaius Julius Caesar in 46 B.C.
Jun 2019
The Forum of Caesar (~525 feet by ~250 feet) is located beside the Via dei Fori Imperiali, Capital Hill (one of the seven hills of Rome) and The Altar of the Fatherland. This was the first of the "imperial" fora. Julius Caesar chose and purchased (supposedly between 60 and 100 million sesterces) this part of the original Roman Forum (~54 B.C.) to construct a forum bearing his name. This ruins is also called Forum Lulium or Forum Julium and Forum Caesaris. Julius Caesar reigned from 46 to 44 B.C. Thus, the Forum of Caesar was started during his tenure as dictator. Originally, Caesar envisioned this project to be an expansion of the Roman Forum. However, during construction the vision changed. Caesar wanted 'his' forum to be a place for public business that was related to the Senate (but not a commercial marketplace) in addition to a shrine for Caesar himself as well as Venus Genetrix. The design was a colonnaded square, with two naves which had porticoes on the long sides in which offices were present for government business to be conducted, and dominated at the far end by the Temple of Venus Genetrix. Many of the colonnades can still be seen today. Why would Julius Caesar chose to honor Venus Genetrix in his forum? The Roman goddess Venus Genetrix is the goddess of motherhood and domesticity. She is the mother of Aeneas, and the mythical ancestress of the Julian family. The Julian family was one of the most ancient patrician families in Ancient Rome. Members of the lineage were the highest dignities of state in the early times of the Roman Republic. The first of the family to obtain the consulship was Gaius Julius Lulus in 489 B.C. The Julian family is perhaps best known for Gaius Julius Caesar, the dictator and grand uncle of the emperor Augustus. The assassination of Julius Caesar in 44 B.C. by Roman senators occurred before this forum was complete. The forum and temple were eventually completed by Octavian in 29 B.C.. Octavian or Julius Caesar Octavianus eventually changed his previous name and became emperor of Rome as Imperator Caesar Augustus. Octavian became monarch in 31 B.C. (or possibly 27 B.C.). Visitors should try to visualize that the location of the Forum of Caesar was originally on a slope of Capital Hill (or Capitone Hill). To allow construction this area first needed to be leveled via the movement of an enormous amount of earth. The enormity of this project should not be underestimated. Actually, the Temple of Venus was rebuilt Domitian after it was damaged by fire in 80 A.D. and rededicated by Trajan in 113 A.D. Its new location was between Capital Hill and Quirinal Hill (another of the seven hills of Rome), after the gap between the two hills was removed. The ruins of the temple can now be seen in what appears to be a section of the Roman Forum below and behind the Altar of the Fatherland. The area of the Forum of Caesar is now ruins. Nonetheless, the historical significance and beauty of this location remain even 2,000+ years later. Definitely a must see when in Rome.
Written August 30, 2019
